SOLD: H&K USP in .40 S&W pistol in flawless condition. This is a Variant 1 which means it has the safety and de-cocker lever. The USP is also a conventional single/ double action semi-auto handgun with a hammer and is not striker fired. 

The USP is a German made pistol that has durability and quality that is superior to most pistols. They were designed to deliver outstanding accuracy and reliable performance through the harshest conditions of warfare. The USP is the civilian version of the famous H&K Mark 23 which was developed for the US SOCOM in the 1990's and with a suppressor, they are an essential weapon for clandestine SEAL offensive operations. In the movie "Tears of the Sun", which is as authentic a Navy SEAL mission movie as I have seen, they show the Mark 23 being used in its quintessential role as they take down a larger force by surprise attack in close quarter battle as they were in the process of "ethnically cleansing" and entire village.

The barrel is cold hammer forged and has polygonal rifling which in the application of a military sidearm, is superior to conventional grooved rifling providing less friction to the bullets passage through the barrel which adds to the amazing durability of the USP. In torture testing, USP's have proven capable of exceeding 90,000 rounds of service! 

This H&K USP is offered with the original case, owner's manual and 2 magazines. This pistol has been a safe queen and has had at most 200 rounds fired through it.

title: For Sale:  BEAUTIFUL WWII GERMAN K98 MAUSER - MINT BORE, BEAUTIFUL SHINE BLUE
postcontent: This one hurts to give up. I will make sure it goes to a good home. First, it has a story. I got this from a close family friend after my high school graduation. His father picked it off of the first German soldier he killed in Italy. He used something to mark the butt of the rifle with a "K" for his last name. It's lightly done and was most likely a pencil or maybe even a rock and grease. It's dark, but doesn't distract from the wood quality and to me, it adds that personalized touch of the soldier. During downtime, he disassembled the rifle and mailed it back to his mother. He survived the war and reassembled the rifle once back in the states. I also have a double sided nazi flag that he brought back as well. I truly hate to lose this piece of my collection, but I need to do some home upgrades. It is a BCD manufacture, which is a bit rarer. The date of manufacture is 1944 where BCD is followed by the digit "4" instead of "44". Manufacturer is Gustloff Werke Weimar (first use of the single-digit year stamp). Bore is bright and mint condition. Wood is in great shape showing natural colors in the grain. Action is tight. Parts are clean. Stamps abound and all serial numbers match. This is truly a safe queen. NEVER reblued and never import stamped. I'll provide the name of the soldier to the buyer. Thank you.
